1. FUNDAMENTAL CONCEPTS
1.1 What is Disability Insurance?
Definition: Insurance that provides income replacement when an individual cannot work due to illness, injury, or disability.
Core Purpose:

Income protection (typically 50-70% of salary)
Financial stability during health crises
Bridge between employment and recovery/return to work

1.2 Disability vs. Absence Management
Disability Management:

Long-term focus (weeks to years)
Medical condition prevents work
Insurance benefit payments
Formal claim process
Medical evidence required

Absence Management:

Short-term focus (days to weeks)
May include non-medical reasons
Employer-paid (usually)
Less formal process
May or may not require medical proof

1.3 Key Terminology
Claimant/Insured: Person filing the disability claim
Policyholder: Entity that purchased the policy (employer or individual)
Beneficiary: Person receiving benefits (usually the claimant)
Elimination Period: Waiting period before benefits begin (like a deductible in time)
Benefit Period: Maximum duration benefits can be paid
Own Occupation: Cannot perform duties of their specific job
Any Occupation: Cannot perform duties of any job suited to their education/experience
Residual/Partial Disability: Can work but with reduced capacity
Total Disability: Cannot work at all
Pre-existing Condition: Medical condition that existed before coverage began
Material and Substantial Duties: Essential functions of a job (usually >50% of duties)

2. TYPES OF DISABILITY COVERAGE
2.1 Short-Term Disability (STD)
Characteristics:

Duration: 3-6 months (typically up to 26 weeks)
Elimination Period: 0-14 days
Benefit Amount: 60-70% of salary
Coverage: Accidents, illnesses, pregnancy
Funding: Usually employer-paid or partially employee-paid

Common Scenarios:

Surgery recovery
Pregnancy/maternity
Broken bones
Mental health crisis (acute)
Recovery from medical procedures

2.2 Long-Term Disability (LTD)
Characteristics:

Duration: 2 years to age 65/67 or lifetime
Elimination Period: 90-180 days (often when STD ends)
Benefit Amount: 50-60% of salary
Maximum Monthly Benefit: Often capped ( 5,000− 15,000/month)
Funding: Employer-paid, employee-paid, or shared

Common Scenarios:

Chronic conditions (MS, lupus, fibromyalgia)
Cancer treatment
Severe mental health conditions
Neurological disorders
Musculoskeletal disorders
Cardiovascular disease

2.3 Group vs. Individual Policies
Group Disability Insurance:

Provided through employer
Standard terms for all employees
Generally less expensive
Limited customization
May be portable (with limitations)
Subject to ERISA (in US)

Individual Disability Insurance:

Purchased by individual
Customizable terms
More expensive
Portable (owned by individual)
Stricter underwriting
Not subject to ERISA

2.4 Statutory vs. Private Disability
Statutory/Government Programs:

Social Security Disability Insurance (SSDI) - US federal program
Workers' Compensation - Work-related injuries
State Disability Insurance (SDI) - California, New York, etc.
Very strict "any occupation" definition
Integration with private insurance

Private Disability Insurance:

Offered by insurance carriers
More flexible definitions
Faster claim processing
Better customer service
Can supplement statutory benefits


3. CLAIM LIFECYCLE
3.1 Pre-Claim Phase
Employee Falls Ill/Gets Injured
↓
Notification to Employer

FMLA notification (if applicable)
Company leave of absence process
HR involvement

Documentation Begins:

Medical documentation
Job description
Salary information
Policy details

3.2 Claim Intake & Registration
Step 1: First Notice of Claim

Methods: Phone, online portal, paper form, mobile app
Information Collected:
Personal identifying information
Employment details
Medical condition (preliminary)
Last day worked
Expected return to work date
Treating physician information
Contact preferences



Step 2: Claim Registration

Claim number assigned
Claim file created in system
Adjuster assigned
Acknowledgment sent to claimant
Employer notification

Step 3: Initial Documentation Request

From Claimant:

Completed claim form
HIPAA authorization
Tax forms (for benefit payments)
Banking information


From Employer:

Salary verification
Job description
Last day worked confirmation
Leave of absence status


From Medical Providers:

Attending Physician Statement (APS)
Medical records
Treatment plans



3.3 Claim Adjudication
Phase 1: Eligibility Verification

Policy active on date of disability?
Premium payments current?
Within coverage period?
Pre-existing condition exclusion apply?
Elimination period satisfied?

Phase 2: Medical Review

Medical criteria:

Diagnosis confirmation
Objective medical evidence
Treatment appropriateness
Prognosis
Functional limitations


Medical Professionals Involved:

Nurse case managers
Medical directors (physicians)
Specialty consultants
Independent medical examiners



Phase 3: Occupational Analysis

Job Analysis:

Physical demands (lifting, standing, etc.)
Cognitive demands
Environmental factors
Material and substantial duties


Capacity Assessment:

Functional Capacity Evaluation (FCE)
Physical restrictions/limitations
Cognitive abilities
Match job demands to medical restrictions



Phase 4: Decision Making

Approved: Benefits begin, payment calculated
Denied: Detailed denial letter with reasons, appeal rights
Pending: Additional information needed

3.4 Ongoing Claim Management
Regular Activities:

Medical Updates

Frequency: Every 30-90 days
Updated medical records
Treatment progress
Change in condition


Return to Work Assessment

Continuous evaluation
Vocational rehabilitation referrals
Transitional work opportunities
Accommodations analysis


Benefit Payments

Calculation verification
Other income offsets (SSDI, Workers' Comp)
Tax handling
Payment delivery


File Documentation

All communications logged
Medical records filed
Decision rationales documented
Compliance with regulations


Surveillance & Investigation (when warranted)

Social media monitoring
Field investigations
Activity checks
Fraud indicators



3.5 Claim Closure
Reasons for Closure:

Recovery & Return to Work

Full duty return
Released by physician
Final payment issued


Maximum Benefit Period Reached

End of benefit period (2 years, age 65, etc.)
Final payment processed
Transition planning


Death of Claimant

Benefits cease
Final payment to estate
Survivor benefits (if applicable)


Failure to Cooperate

Didn't submit medical updates
Refused IME
Unreachable


No Longer Disabled

Medical improvement
Can perform own/any occupation


Conversion to SSDI/Other Benefits

Offset arrangements



Closure Activities:

Final payment calculation
Tax forms (1099)
Closure letter
File retention per regulations
Data archiving


4. KEY STAKEHOLDERS
4.1 Internal Stakeholders
Claim Examiners/Adjudicators

Role: Primary decision-makers on claims
Responsibilities: Evaluate medical evidence, determine eligibility, approve/deny claims
Skills Needed: Medical knowledge, policy interpretation, critical thinking

Nurse Case Managers

Role: Medical liaison and case coordination
Responsibilities: Review medical records, coordinate care, facilitate RTW
Background: Registered nurses with case management certification

Medical Directors

Role: Physician oversight and complex case review
Responsibilities: Final medical authority, peer-to-peer with treating doctors, policy development
Background: Licensed physicians (MD/DO)

Vocational Rehabilitation Consultants

Role: Return to work facilitation
Responsibilities: Job analysis, accommodation recommendations, retraining assessment
Background: Vocational rehabilitation certification

Special Investigation Unit (SIU)

Role: Fraud detection and investigation
Responsibilities: Investigate suspicious claims, surveillance, evidence gathering

Customer Service Representatives

Role: First point of contact
Responsibilities: Answer inquiries, process documents, status updates

Claims Management/Supervisors

Role: Oversight and quality assurance
Responsibilities: Complex case consultation, appeals, compliance

Actuaries

Role: Risk assessment and pricing
Responsibilities: Reserve setting, pricing models, trend analysis

IT/Systems Administrators

Role: Technology support
Responsibilities: System maintenance, data integrity, reporting

4.2 External Stakeholders
Claimants

Primary beneficiary
Must cooperate with claim process
Rights to appeal

Employers/HR Departments

Provide salary/job information
Coordinate return to work
Manage internal leave processes
May influence claim outcomes (accommodation discussions)

Treating Physicians

Provide medical documentation
Certify disability
Release to return to work
Most influential voice in claim

Independent Medical Examiners (IME)

Objective medical assessment
Not treating relationship
Used when conflict or clarification needed

Attorneys (Claimant)

Represent claimants in appeals
More common in LTD denials
Navigate ERISA process

Third-Party Administrators (TPAs)

Administer claims for self-insured employers
Act on behalf of insurance company

Social Security Administration

SSDI coordination
Offset calculations
Information sharing

Regulatory Bodies

DOL (Department of Labor) - ERISA oversight
State Insurance Departments - Compliance
HIPAA - Privacy compliance

Reinsurers

Share risk on large claims
Oversight on high-value cases


5. MEDICAL & CLINICAL ASPECTS
5.1 Medical Evidence Hierarchy
1. Objective Medical Evidence (Most Valuable)

Lab results
Imaging (MRI, X-ray, CT scans)
EMG/nerve conduction studies
Pathology reports
Surgical findings
Physical examination findings

2. Clinical Findings

Treatment notes
Hospital records
Physical therapy progress notes
Medication records
Specialist consultations

3. Subjective Reports

Patient reported symptoms
Pain scales
Functional questionnaires
Quality of life measures

5.2 Common Disability Diagnoses
Musculoskeletal Disorders (30-35% of claims)

Back pain (lumbar, cervical)
Herniated discs
Degenerative disc disease
Arthritis
Fibromyalgia
Complex Regional Pain Syndrome (CRPS)
Post-surgical complications

Considerations:

Often subjective (pain-based)
Functional capacity testing important
Treatment compliance critical
High potential for recovery

Mental/Behavioral Health (20-25% of claims)

Major depression
Anxiety disorders
Bipolar disorder
PTSD
Schizophrenia
Substance abuse disorders

Considerations:

Subjective symptoms
Treatment compliance crucial
Medication effectiveness
Cognitive functional assessments
Stigma and disclosure issues

Cancer/Neoplasms (10-15% of claims)

Various cancer types
Treatment-related disability (chemo, radiation)
Post-surgical recovery

Considerations:

Often clear-cut initially
Treatment side effects
Prognosis varies widely
May have recovery or recurrence

Cardiovascular (8-10% of claims)

Heart attack
Heart failure
Stroke
Peripheral vascular disease

Considerations:

Objective testing available
Physical capacity limitations
Often age-related
Risk of recurrence

Neurological (8-10% of claims)

Multiple Sclerosis
Parkinson's disease
Epilepsy
Neuropathy
Traumatic brain injury

Considerations:

Progressive conditions
Variable functional impact
Medication management
Cognitive and physical limitations

Injuries/Accidents (5-8% of claims)

Fractures
Traumatic injuries
Motor vehicle accidents
Workplace injuries

Considerations:

Usually time-limited
Clear causation
Recovery expected
May overlap with Workers' Comp

5.3 Functional Assessment
Activities of Daily Living (ADLs)

Bathing
Dressing
Eating
Toileting
Transferring (movement)
Continence

Instrumental Activities of Daily Living (IADLs)

Managing finances
Managing medications
Shopping
Meal preparation
Housekeeping
Using transportation

Work-Related Functional Capacities

Physical:

Lifting/carrying (occasional/frequent)
Standing/walking duration
Sitting tolerance
Reaching, grasping, handling
Climbing, balancing, stooping


Cognitive:

Memory (short/long-term)
Concentration
Processing speed
Decision-making
Multi-tasking


Sensory:

Vision
Hearing
Speech



5.4 Treatment Expectations
Treatment Compliance

Following prescribed treatment
Attending appointments
Taking medications as prescribed
Participating in therapy
Following restrictions

Reasonable Treatment

Evidence-based medicine
Appropriate for condition
Not experimental
Risk vs. benefit acceptable

Maximum Medical Improvement (MMI)

Point where further treatment won't improve condition
Important milestone in claims
May still be disabled but condition stable


6. LEGAL & REGULATORY FRAMEWORK
6.1 ERISA (Employee Retirement Income Security Act)
Applicability: Most employer-sponsored disability plans in US
Key Provisions:

Fiduciary Duty: Plan administrators must act in participants' best interest
Claims Procedures: Strict timelines for decisions and appeals
Disclosure Requirements: Summary Plan Description (SPD)
Preemption: Federal law supersedes state law

Claim Timelines:

Initial Decision: 45 days (with two 30-day extensions possible)
Appeal: 45 days to file; 45 days for decision (one 45-day extension)
Notification: Must include specific reasons for denial, plan provisions, appeal rights

Full and Fair Review:

Access to all relevant documents
Submit evidence
Review of decision by different person
No deference to initial decision

6.2 ADA (Americans with Disabilities Act)
Relevance: Affects return to work and accommodation
Key Concepts:

Qualified Individual: Can perform essential functions with or without accommodation
Reasonable Accommodation: Modifications that don't cause undue hardship
Interactive Process: Employer and employee dialogue
Undue Hardship: Significant difficulty or expense

Accommodations Examples:

Modified work schedule
Ergonomic equipment
Assistive technology
Restructured job duties
Telework options

6.3 FMLA (Family and Medical Leave Act)
Interaction with Disability:

12 weeks unpaid leave for serious health condition
Job protection (not income)
Runs concurrently with disability leave
Medical certification required

Serious Health Condition:

Inpatient care
Continuing treatment by healthcare provider
Chronic serious health condition
Permanent/long-term conditions

6.4 HIPAA (Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act)
Privacy in Claims:

Protected Health Information (PHI): Medical records, diagnoses, treatment
Authorization Required: Claimant must authorize release
Minimum Necessary: Only relevant information shared
Security: Electronic and physical safeguards

Breach Implications:

Fines and penalties
Reputational damage
Individual lawsuits

6.5 State Regulations
Vary by State:

Prompt payment laws
Grace periods
Rescission limitations
Bad faith penalties
Statute of limitations

State Disability Programs:

California SDI: State-run disability insurance
New York DBL: Disability Benefits Law
New Jersey TDI: Temporary Disability Insurance
Rhode Island TDI
Hawaii TDI
Puerto Rico

6.6 Tax Implications
Premium Payment:

Employer-paid premiums: Benefits taxable
Employee-paid premiums (after-tax): Benefits non-taxable
Employee-paid premiums (pre-tax/cafeteria plan): Benefits taxable

Reporting:

1099 forms for taxable benefits
W-2 reporting by employers


7. FINANCIAL COMPONENTS
7.1 Benefit Calculation
Base Benefit Formula:
Monthly Benefit = (Covered Earnings × Benefit Percentage) - Offsets
Covered Earnings:

Usually base salary
May include bonuses, commissions
Excludes overtime (typically)
Definition varies by policy

Benefit Percentage:

STD: 60-70%
LTD: 50-60%

Maximum Benefit:

Monthly cap (e.g., $10,000/month)
Weekly cap for STD
Limits total payout

Example:
Salary: $80,000/year ($6,667/month)
LTD Percentage: 60%
Maximum: $5,000/month

Calculation: $6,667 × 0.60 = $4,000
Benefit: $4,000/month (under maximum)
7.2 Offsets and Integrations
Other Income Offsets (reduce disability benefit):

Social Security Disability Insurance (SSDI)

Most common offset
Includes dependent benefits
May be estimated until approved
Can create overpayment issues


Workers' Compensation

If injury work-related
Settlements complicate calculations


State Disability Benefits

SDI in California, etc.


Retirement Benefits

If taken while disabled
Pension payments


Earnings from Work

If working part-time
May encourage return to work



Offset Calculation Example:
Gross LTD Benefit: $4,000/month
SSDI Benefit: $2,000/month
Net LTD Benefit: $4,000 - $2,000 = $2,000/month
All-Source Maximum:

Total disability income limited to percentage of pre-disability earnings (often 80-85%)
Prevents over-insurance

7.3 Reserve Setting
Purpose: Estimate future claim costs
Methods:

Case Reserves

Claim-specific estimate
Based on expected duration and benefit amount
Updated regularly


IBNR (Incurred But Not Reported)

Claims that occurred but not yet filed
Statistical estimation


Formula:


Reserve = (Monthly Benefit × Expected Duration) + Expenses
Factors Affecting Reserves:

Claimant age
Diagnosis
Occupation
Treatment plan
Historical claim data

7.4 Overpayments and Recoveries
Causes of Overpayment:

SSDI approval (retroactive)
Unreported return to work
Unreported other income
System errors

Recovery Methods:

Offset from future payments
Direct repayment plan
Legal action (last resort)
Write-off (if uncollectible)

Challenges:

Financial hardship for claimants
Legal limitations
Administrative costs

7.5 Cost Management Strategies
For Insurance Companies:

Early Intervention

Nurse case management
Reduce claim duration
Facilitate treatment


Return to Work Programs

Vocational rehabilitation
Transitional work
Accommodations


Medical Management

Ensure appropriate treatment
Second opinions
Independent medical exams


Fraud Prevention

Investigation
Surveillance
Analytics


Litigation Management

Proper documentation
Defensible decisions
Early legal consultation




