9. FRAUD DETECTION & PREVENTION
9.1 Types of Disability Fraud
Claimant Fraud:

Exaggerated Symptoms

Overstating pain or limitations
Functional abilities exceed reported


Fabricated Condition

No actual medical condition
False medical documentation


Unreported Work

Working while collecting benefits
Cash jobs
Self-employment


Unreported Recovery

Improved but not reported
Released to work but doesn't notify


Unreported Other Income

SSDI, Workers' Comp, pensions
To avoid offset



Provider Fraud:

False medical documentation
Kickback schemes
Unnecessary treatment
Billing for services not rendered

Employer Fraud:

False salary information
Collusion with employee
Premium evasion

Internal Fraud:

Adjuster collusion
Unauthorized payments
Identity theft

9.2 Red Flags & Indicators
Medical Red Flags:

Diagnosis not supported by objective findings
Treatment inconsistent with condition
Doctor shopping
Gaps in treatment
Refused recommended treatment
Attorney involvement early in claim
Delayed reporting of injury

Behavioral Red Flags:

Inconsistent statements
Evasive or uncooperative
Financial problems (bankruptcy, foreclosure)
History of multiple claims
Complaint about employer/job
Filed claim near end of employment

Activity Red Flags:

Social media shows activities inconsistent with restrictions
Unreachable during business hours
Operating a business
Observed activities exceed reported abilities

Financial Red Flags:

High-dollar claim
Premium recently increased
Policy about to lapse
Near maximum benefit period

9.3 Investigation Techniques
Desktop Investigation:

Social Media Monitoring

Public profiles (Facebook, Instagram, LinkedIn)
Photos/videos of activities
Check-ins at locations
Posts about work or activities


Public Records Search

Business registrations
Property records
Court records
License databases


Internet Search

Personal websites
Online reviews (if self-employed)
News articles
Professional profiles



Field Investigation:

Surveillance

Video documentation
Activity logs
3-5 days typical duration
Physical activities documented


Scene Investigation

Accident site (if relevant)
Workplace
Residence


Interviews

Neighbors
Coworkers
Witnesses



Medical Investigation:

Independent Medical Examination (IME)

Objective assessment
Functional capacity evaluation
Consistency with reported symptoms


Medical Record Review

Complete history
Treatment patterns
Inconsistencies


Peer Review

Medical director evaluation
Guideline adherence



Data Analytics:

Predictive modeling
Pattern recognition
Network analysis
Anomaly detection

9.4 Investigation Process
Step 1: Referral to SIU

Triggered by red flags
Adjuster referral
Automated analytics alert

Step 2: Initial Review

Case summary
Red flag documentation
Preliminary research
Investigation plan

Step 3: Investigation

Execute investigation techniques
Gather evidence
Document findings

Step 4: Analysis

Evaluate evidence
Legal consultation
Determine fraud likelihood

Step 5: Action

Claim denial (if fraud proven)
Benefit termination
Demand letter for repayment
Law enforcement referral (criminal fraud)
Civil litigation

Step 6: Documentation

Investigation report
Evidence preservation
File notation
Reporting to databases (NICB, state fraud bureaus)

9.5 Legal & Ethical Considerations
Legal Boundaries:

No trespassing
No harassment
Privacy laws vary by state
Public vs. private space
Recorded communications laws

Ethics:

Balance fraud prevention with claimant dignity
Investigate facts, not assumptions
Cultural sensitivity
Avoid bias

Defense:

Proper documentation critical
Chain of custody for evidence
Admissibility in court
Expert witnesses


10. BEST PRACTICES & INDUSTRY STANDARDS
10.1 Best Practices in Claims Management
1. Early Intervention

Contact claimant within 24-48 hours
Nurse case manager involvement early
Treatment plan review
Set expectations

2. Consistent Communication

Regular status updates
Clear explanations
Multiple contact methods
Respect claimant preferences

3. Medical Management

Evidence-based medicine
Appropriate specialist involvement
Treatment progress monitoring
Barrier identification

4. Return to Work Focus

Begin planning at claim start
Transitional work options
Accommodation discussions
Vocational rehabilitation when needed

5. Documentation Excellence

Every contact documented
Rationales for decisions
Medical evidence summarized
Timeline of events

6. Empathy & Customer Service

Recognize stress of disability
Non-judgmental approach
Trauma-informed care
Respect and dignity

7. Collaboration

Employer partnership
Treating provider communication
Multi-disciplinary team approach
Claimant as team member

8. Technology Utilization

Automated workflows
Data analytics
Self-service options
Mobile accessibility

9. Compliance

Regulatory adherence
Quality audits
Training programs
Policy updates

10. Continuous Improvement

Metrics monitoring
Process optimization
Feedback incorporation
Industry benchmarking

10.2 Key Performance Indicators (KPIs)
Operational KPIs:

Claim Intake to Assignment: <1 business day
First Payment Timeliness: 95% within 5 days of approval
Claim Closure Rate: % of inventory closed monthly
Average Cycle Time: Days from report to decision
Pending Inventory: Number and age

Quality KPIs:

Approval Accuracy: % of approvals that remain approved (no overturn)
Denial Overturn Rate: <10% on appeal
Customer Satisfaction Score: >85%
Documentation Quality Score: Audit results
Compliance Score: Regulatory audit results

Financial KPIs:

Loss Ratio: Paid claims / earned premium
Expense Ratio: Operating expenses / premium
Reserve Accuracy: Actual vs. predicted
Average Claim Cost: By diagnosis, duration
Recovery Rate: Overpayment collections

Return to Work KPIs:

RTW Rate: % returning to work
Average Duration: Days on claim
Accommodation Success Rate: % successful accommodations
Recurrence Rate: % who become disabled again

Medical Management KPIs:

Nurse Case Management Penetration: % of claims with NCM
IME Utilization Rate: When needed vs. ordered
Treatment Guideline Adherence: By providers
Maximum Medical Improvement: Average time to MMI

