11. PRACTICAL CLAIM SCENARIOS
Scenario 1: Simple STD Claim - Post-Surgical Recovery
Facts:

Employee: Sarah, age 35, office worker
Condition: Gallbladder removal (laparoscopic)
Surgery date: March 15
Last day worked: March 14
Expected duration: 2-4 weeks
Elimination period: 7 days

Claim Process:

Day 1 - Sarah calls to file claim
Day 2 - Claim registered, forms sent
Day 5 - Forms received, medical records requested
Day 8 - Medical records received, reviewed by nurse
Day 10 - Claim approved, 3-week duration
Day 14 - First check issued
Week 3 - Physician releases Sarah to full duty
Week 4 - Sarah returns to work, claim closes

Key Points:

Straightforward medical condition
Clear objective evidence (surgical report)
Expected recovery timeline
No complications

Scenario 2: Complex LTD Claim - Fibromyalgia
Facts:

Employee: John, age 45, warehouse worker
Condition: Fibromyalgia
Last day worked: January 5
Physical job requirements: Lifting 50+ lbs, 8 hours standing
STD claim paid for 6 months
Now filing LTD claim

Claim Challenges:

Subjective condition (pain-based)
No objective medical tests
Treatment effectiveness unclear
Job is very physical
Potential for improvement with treatment

Claim Process:

Month 6 - LTD claim filed
Week 1-2 - Medical records reviewed
Diagnosis confirmed by rheumatologist
Multiple treatments tried
Functional limitations documented


Week 3 - Nurse case manager assigned
Calls treating physician
Reviews treatment options
Discusses work restrictions


Week 4 - Occupational analysis
Job requires frequent lifting over restrictions
Material and substantial duties affected
No sedentary duties available


Week 5 - Claim approved
"Own occupation" met
Vocational rehabilitation referral
Benefits begin


Ongoing - Every 3 months
Medical updates required
Treatment compliance monitored
RTW assessment
Vocational evaluation



Key Points:

Documentation critical
Treatment compliance required
Clear functional restrictions
Match restrictions to job demands
Ongoing management intensive
Vocational rehabilitation important

Scenario 3: Denied Claim with Appeal - Depression
Facts:

Employee: Maria, age 28, accountant
Condition: Major depression
Last day worked: September 1
STD claim filed and initially denied
Reason for denial: Lack of objective evidence

Initial Denial Rationale:

Medical records show diagnosis but limited treatment
Only 2 therapy sessions
Medication prescribed but no follow-up
No hospitalization
Functional capacity not clearly documented

Appeal Process:

Week 1 - Maria receives denial letter
Consults with attorney
Requests claim file


Week 2 - Attorney reviews file
Identifies gaps in medical documentation
Advises Maria to get comprehensive evaluation


Week 3-4 - Additional medical evidence
Psychiatrist evaluation
Detailed functional assessment
Cognitive testing
Hospitalization after suicide ideation


Week 5 - Appeal submitted
New medical evidence
Attorney letter
Personal statement from Maria


Week 6-8 - Appeal review
Different adjuster assigned
Medical director review
All new evidence considered


Week 9 - Appeal approved
Benefits paid retroactively
Ongoing treatment plan
Return to work planning begins



Key Points:

Initial denial may be appropriate with limited evidence
Appeals allow for additional evidence
Mental health claims require robust documentation
Treatment compliance critical
Functional impact must be clear

Scenario 4: Fraud Investigation
Facts:

Employee: David, age 52, construction supervisor
Condition: Back injury
Claim duration: 18 months on LTD
Red flags emerge

Red Flags:

Social media posts show David at construction sites
Neighbor reports seeing David doing heavy yard work
Surveillance footage from gym shows heavy lifting
Recently started LLC (construction consulting)

Investigation:

Week 1 - Referral to SIU
Red flags documented
Investigation plan created


Week 2-3 - Surveillance ordered
5 days of surveillance
Video shows:
Lifting 50+ lbs
Climbing ladders
Extended standing/walking
Working at construction site




Week 4 - Additional investigation
LLC documents show active business
Bank records show income
Social media archived


Week 5 - Medical review
Activities exceed stated restrictions
Inconsistent with reported pain level
Functional abilities demonstrated


Week 6 - Claim decision
Claim terminated
Overpayment demand letter ($54,000)
Fraud referral to state authorities


Ongoing - Recovery and prosecution
Civil demand for repayment
Potential criminal charges
Employer notified



Key Points:

Multiple sources of evidence needed
Legal consultation throughout
Documentation critical for defense
Clear policy language on fraud
Recovery efforts

Scenario 5: Return to Work Success
Facts:

Employee: Lisa, age 40, customer service manager
Condition: Breast cancer with chemotherapy
LTD claim active for 8 months
Treatment completed, in remission

Return to Work Plan:

Month 8 - Medical clearance discussion
Oncologist clears for work with limitations
Fatigue and cognitive effects lingering
Recommends gradual return


Week 1 - RTW planning meeting
Participants: Lisa, employer, adjuster, vocational counselor
Options discussed:
Part-time schedule
Modified duties
Work from home options
Graduated return




Week 2 - Accommodation analysis
Essential functions identified
Temporary modifications acceptable to employer:
20 hours/week for 4 weeks
Then 30 hours/week for 4 weeks
Then full-time
Flexible schedule
Reduced travel




Week 3 - Trial return to work begins
Partial disability benefits continue
Earnings offset from LTD benefit
Close monitoring


Months 3-4 - Graduated increase
Energy improving
Cognitive function returning
Performance meeting expectations


Month 4 - Full duty return
LTD claim closes
Accommodations no longer needed
Follow-up call at 6 months



Financial Impact:
LTD Benefit: $4,000/month
Part-time earnings (20 hrs): $2,000/month
Net LTD payment: $2,000/month
Total income: $4,000/month (maintained)

Benefit to all:
- Lisa: Income maintained, easier transition
- Employer: Retains valued employee, minimizes accommodations
- Insurer: Reduces claim cost, positive outcome
Key Points:

Early RTW planning
Collaboration among all parties
Flexible accommodations
Graduated return reduces risk
Financial incentives aligned
Monitoring and support


