12.2 Non-Functional Requirements
Performance:

Page load time: <3 seconds
Report generation: <30 seconds for standard reports
Search results: <2 seconds
Payment processing: Real-time authorization
System availability: 99.9% uptime

Scalability:

Support 10,000+ concurrent users
Handle 100,000+ active claims
Store 10+ years of claim history
Process 50,000+ documents daily

Usability:

Intuitive interface
Minimal training required
Accessibility (WCAG 2.1 AA compliant)
Responsive design
Contextual help

Security:

Encryption (AES-256)
Multi-factor authentication
Password complexity requirements
Automatic session timeout
Penetration testing (annual)
Vulnerability scanning

Compliance:

HIPAA compliant
SOC 2 Type II certified
ERISA compliant
ADA accessible
GDPR ready (if applicable)

Disaster Recovery:

Recovery Time Objective (RTO): <4 hours
Recovery Point Objective (RPO): <1 hour
Regular backups (daily)
Offsite backup storage
Disaster recovery testing (quarterly)


13. GLOSSARY OF TERMS
Adjudication: The process of reviewing and deciding on a disability claim.
Any Occupation: Definition of disability where claimant cannot perform any job for which they are reasonably qualified by education, training, or experience.
Appeal: Request for reconsideration of a denied or terminated claim.
Attending Physician Statement (APS): Formal medical report from treating doctor about patient's condition and functional limitations.
Benefit Period: Maximum duration for which benefits can be paid under a policy.
Case Reserve: Estimated amount set aside to pay future benefits on an open claim.
COBRA: Consolidated Omnibus Budget Reconciliation Act - allows continuation of health insurance after employment ends.
Comorbidity: Presence of multiple medical conditions simultaneously.
Concurrent Review: Ongoing evaluation of medical treatment while claimant is disabled.
Date of Disability (DOD): Date when disability begins (may differ from last day worked).
Elimination Period: Waiting period before benefits begin (similar to insurance deductible but in time).
ERISA: Employee Retirement Income Security Act - federal law governing employer-sponsored benefit plans.
Essential Functions: Core job duties that are fundamental to the position.
Evidence of Insurability (EOI): Medical information required for coverage, especially for amounts over guaranteed issue.
Experience Rating: Method of setting premiums based on claims history.
FMLA: Family and Medical Leave Act - provides job-protected unpaid leave for serious health conditions.
Functional Capacity Evaluation (FCE): Objective assessment of physical abilities.
Guaranteed Issue: Coverage amount available without medical underwriting.
HIPAA: Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act - governs privacy of health information.
Impairment: Loss of function or abnormality in body structure or physiological function.
Incurred But Not Reported (IBNR): Claims that have occurred but not yet been filed.
Independent Medical Examination (IME): Medical evaluation by non-treating physician for objective assessment.
Integration/Offset: Reduction of disability benefits by other income sources.
Material and Substantial Duties: Important job responsibilities that cannot be eliminated without fundamentally changing the job.
Maximum Medical Improvement (MMI): Point where further improvement is not expected with treatment.
Occupational Disease: Illness caused by work conditions or exposures.
Own Occupation: Definition of disability where claimant cannot perform duties of their specific job.
Pre-existing Condition: Medical condition that existed before coverage began.
Presumptive Disability: Automatic approval for certain catastrophic conditions (e.g., total blindness, loss of two limbs).
Recurrent Disability: Return of same or related condition after recovery.
Rehabilitation: Services to help claimant return to work.
Residual Disability: Partial disability where claimant can work but with reduced capacity and earnings.
Return to Work (RTW): Process of transitioning back to employment after disability.
Social Security Disability Insurance (SSDI): Federal disability program based on work history.
Subjective Complaints: Symptoms reported by patient that cannot be objectively verified (e.g., pain).
Subrogation: Insurance company's right to recover payments from third parties responsible for disability.
Summary Plan Description (SPD): ERISA-required document explaining plan benefits and rights.
Total Disability: Complete inability to work as defined by policy.
Transitional Work: Modified or light duty work to facilitate return to employment.
Vocational Rehabilitation: Services to help claimant develop new work skills.
Waiting Period: See Elimination Period.
Workers' Compensation: State-mandated insurance for work-related injuries and illnesses.

